(11. One problem with \(Python\) docstrings is that they're local) Tj
T*
(Source: Chris's Wiki :: blog | Published: 2026-03-19T02:41:13Z) Tj
T*
(Link: https://utcc.utoronto.ca/~cks/space/blog/python/DocstringsAreLocal) Tj
T*
(When I wrote about documenting my Django forms , I said that I knew I didn't want to put my) Tj
T*
(documentation in docstrings, because I'd written some in the past and then not read it this) Tj
T*
(time around. One of the reasons for that is that Python docstrings have to be attached to) Tj
T*
(functions, or more generally, Python docstrings have to be scattered through your code. The) Tj
T*
(corollary to this is that to find relevant docstrings you have to read through your code and) Tj
T*
(then remember which bits of it are relevant to what you're wondering about. When your docstring) Tj
T*
(is specifically about the function you already know you want to look at, this is fine.) Tj
T*
(Docstrings work perfectly well for local knowledge, for 'what is this function about' summaries) Tj
T*
(that you want to read before you delve into the function. I feel they work rather less well for) Tj
T*
(finding what function you want to look at \(ideally you want some sort of skimmable index for) Tj
